# Knowledge quiz — TEACHING format. The KNOWLEDGE is the PRINCIPLE (transferable);
# the domain (power=1.0, code 351, ...) is just the concrete scar that taught it.
# A question is only worth asking if it builds a principle that survives a project change.
# fields: id | principle (the transferable law — the real knowledge) | level (L1..L3)
#         when? (regex, for opt-in quiz-gate) | context | q | naive | why | a
#
# ---- principles you can carry to ANY project ----
{"id": "M1", "principle": "evidence-over-non-crash", "level": "L1", "when": "修好了|fixed|搞定|解决了|跑通了", "context": "Training finished, inference ran with no error, and the loss curve dropped all the way; you want to confirm the implementation is correct.", "q": "Inference didn't crash and loss is dropping — does that prove the implementation is correct?", "naive": "Yes, it runs, so it's right.", "why": "Multimodal bugs are often silent: loss uses teacher-forcing (fed GT), train and infer run the SAME wrong code -> consistently wrong, loss still drops. A crash needs a type/shape error; a logic error (shift/mask/weights) doesn't crash.", "a": "Principle: 'no crash' is never 'logic correct'; only falsifiable verification (ablation/probe/generation through the model) verifies it. The silent multimodal bug is just one instance."}
{"id": "M2", "principle": "eval-through-the-system-not-a-proxy", "level": "L2", "when": "\\.wav|demo|发我|发你|听.{0,2}听", "context": "You have a demo that sounds a lot like the reference answer, and want to use it to prove the model trained well.", "q": "The demo sounds like the answer — how do you tell it actually went through the system under test?", "naive": "If it sounds like the answer, that's enough.", "why": "The demo could be GT run through the codec (encode->decode), never through the model — a codec round-trip only tests reconstruction, so even a terrible model 'sounds like the answer' this way.", "a": "Principle: eval must go end-to-end through the system under test, not a proxy/reconstruction; it only counts if you can point at the line where the system was called. codec-roundtrip-as-demo is the instance."}
{"id": "M3", "principle": "isolate-one-variable", "level": "L2", "context": "You want to know whether batch 64 or 512 gives better audio quality, so you trained one of each and listened.", "q": "Can this comparison yield a conclusion?", "naive": "Just run one of each and listen.", "why": "Beyond batch, the two runs may differ in epoch/turn-taking/temperature; the difference could be a confound, not batch.", "a": "Principle: a comparison must change ONE variable and hold the rest fixed, or you can't attribute the result. The batch comparison is just an instance."}
{"id": "M4", "principle": "n=1-is-not-a-law", "level": "L2", "context": "You saw a bug on one ckpt and not on another.", "q": "Can you conclude some change caused it?", "naive": "Sure, it's there or it isn't.", "why": "Generation is stochastic (temp>0); the same model with a different seed/sample shows it sometimes. One observation can't separate a system problem from noise.", "a": "Principle: a single observation of a stochastic system isn't a law; look at the frequency over many. Sampling noise is the instance."}
{"id": "M5", "principle": "verify-data-before-blaming-algorithm", "level": "L2", "when": "illegal.?mem|CUDA|崩|hang|OOM|NaN", "context": "Training crashes in backward with CUDA illegal memory access.", "q": "What do you check first?", "naive": "Probably bf16 instability / long-sequence attention.", "why": "illegal-mem is often a NaN/bad value in the input: a file on unreliable storage got corrupted on read -> wav decodes to garbage -> forward inf/nan -> backward illegal access.", "a": "Principle: when it crashes at an IO/numeric boundary, verify input data integrity first, then hypothesize about the algorithm. A JFS-corrupted wav is the instance."}
{"id": "M6", "principle": "smoke-before-scale", "level": "L2", "when": "sbatch|torchrun|训练", "context": "You plan to run the full job at per_device=16 but aren't sure it'll OOM.", "q": "Just launch the full run?", "naive": "Run it and see; deal with a crash if it comes.", "why": "OOM/backward crashes surface at step one; gambling on a blind run means waiting hours in the queue for a GPU only to crash.", "a": "Principle: before an expensive, irreversible action, do a minimal-scale smoke test. The OOM probe is the instance."}
{"id": "M7", "principle": "custom-code-drifts-from-reference", "level": "L3", "when": "duplex/(model|dataset|inference)|modeling|speech_dataset", "context": "You edited the duplex loss/forward code following your own idea.", "q": "What should your default assumption be afterward?", "naive": "My change is probably right.", "why": "Your code forked from a verified reference (base); any override can silently drop a key base step (e.g. the AR shift), and it won't crash.", "a": "Principle: any custom change to a verified reference is assumed to introduce a silent drift; diff line-by-line and log a reason per divergence. The dropped AR-shift is the instance."}
{"id": "M8", "principle": "verify-the-artifact-not-the-exit-code", "level": "L2", "when": "跑完|完成了|finished|done\\b", "context": "A data-processing job finished, exit 0, and the line count is right.", "q": "Can you move to the next stage?", "naive": "It finished, so we're good.", "why": "exit 0 + right line count only means 'finished without crashing', not that each record's content/schema/fields are right; bad records flow silently downstream.", "a": "Principle: 'finished without crashing' != 'artifact correct'; sample and verify content before moving on. The data-job spot-check is the instance."}
{"id": "D1", "principle": "sequence-length-is-computable", "level": "L1", "context": "You want to estimate how many tokens 30s of audio is, to check the context budget.", "q": "How many tokens is 30s? What does it depend on?", "naive": "Just convert from the duration to a number.", "why": "Audio token count = fixed frame rate x RVQ layers, a design constant; more layers = more tokens for the same duration.", "a": "Principle: a tokenized representation has a fixed rate; sequence length is a computable hard constraint, not a guess. The RVQ frame-rate x layers is the instance."}
{"id": "D2", "principle": "frozen-component-contract", "level": "L2", "when": "np\\.zeros", "context": "Synthesizing dialogue data, there are gaps between turns and you fill the silence with np.zeros.", "q": "Is filling silence with pure zeros OK?", "naive": "Zero is no sound, so yes.", "why": "The frozen tokenizer has only seen real recordings (with floor noise), never pure zeros; pure zeros are OOD -> map to a fixed garbage code (351), ~40% of training targets.", "a": "Principle: a no-op/padding region fed to a frozen component is OOD; you must check what it actually encodes to. zeros->351 is the instance."}
{"id": "D3", "principle": "frozen-component-contract", "level": "L2", "when": "MelSpectrogram|mel_spectrogram|encode|编码", "context": "You write an encode script turning wav into a mel spectrogram for the tokenizer, and torchaudio's MelSpectrogram is called without power.", "q": "Is the default power=2.0 OK?", "naive": "The default should be fine.", "why": "The tokenizer was trained and frozen with power=1.0 (magnitude); the default 2.0 (energy) -> squared -> doubled in log -> OOD.", "a": "Principle: preprocessing fed to a frozen pretrained component must match its training config bit-for-bit; don't trust library defaults. mel power=1.0 is just the instance (for CLIP it'd be image norm)."}
{"id": "D4", "principle": "capability-word-is-a-codesign", "level": "L3", "context": "You want full-duplex speech: the model listens to the user while also speaking.", "q": "What is full-duplex training, really?", "naive": "A training mode / a switch.", "why": "It requires the audio+text streams aligned to real time, each head computing a different loss at different positions, plus an onset state machine to decide when to start speaking.", "a": "Principle: a capability word is a co-design of data+architecture+loss, not a switch; decompose it into mechanisms before implementing. full-duplex is the instance (this one leans domain)."}
{"id": "D5", "principle": "align-multi-stream-rates", "level": "L3", "context": "At inference the model finishes the text but the audio runs on, piled up at the end.", "q": "Why?", "naive": "An inference bug.", "why": "AR generates group by group: a 5-token text block takes ~0.8s but its audio takes 1.6s; the rates aren't aligned, so the model learned 'dump the text first, drag the audio out'.", "a": "Principle: multiple AR streams at different rates learn to de-sync; align the rates at the data level. text/audio rate-coupling is the instance."}
{"id": "D6", "principle": "majority-class-loss-weight-sets-behavior", "level": "L3", "context": "At inference the model talks non-stop / repeats, and you want to tune temperature.", "q": "Can tuning temperature fix it?", "naive": "Yes, it's a sampling problem, tune temperature.", "why": "In duplex ~95% of positions target empty, but empty_loss_weight=0.01 is too low -> the model under-trains 'stay quiet' -> spews words.", "a": "Principle: the loss weight on the majority target class decides whether the model learns to abstain; inherited default weights are often tuned for a different distribution. empty_loss_weight is the instance."}
{"id": "D7", "principle": "info-set-must-match-deployment-causality", "level": "L3", "when": "encoder|streaming|流式|causal", "context": "You want to deploy the model streaming, using a bidirectional encoder.", "q": "Is a bidirectional encoder OK for streaming?", "naive": "Bidirectional is better, so yes.", "why": "A bidirectional encoder attends the whole segment, so 'now's' code already encodes 'the future'; offline you give it the whole thing -> timing looks perfect, streaming has only up-to-now -> codes are OOD, the future cue is gone -> it breaks.", "a": "Principle: a non-causal representation leaks the future into the present; offline full-context eval != streaming causal deployment. The bidirectional audio encoder is the instance."}
{"id": "D8", "principle": "train-infer-parity", "level": "L3", "context": "You notice training has an audio loss target every tick and inference generates audio every tick, and worry it's a bug.", "q": "Is it a bug?", "naive": "Inference shouldn't emit audio constantly — bug.", "why": "Inference must reproduce training conditions: training computes audio loss every tick (no mask), so generating every tick is a faithful reproduction.", "a": "Principle: inference must reproduce training's mask/gate/shift/flag bit-for-bit; matching is correct, train-has-but-infer-doesn't (or vice versa) is the bug. The every-tick audio is the instance."}
{"id": "D9", "principle": "backward-is-the-memory-bottleneck", "level": "L3", "when": "sbatch|torchrun|per_device|eff.?batch", "context": "You want effective batch=512 and your instinct is to set per_device to 16.", "q": "Just per_device=16?", "naive": "Stacking per_device is the most direct.", "why": "Forward memory is fine, but backward (gradients+activations) peak scales linearly with per_device -> illegal-mem/OOM; grad-accum sums gradients without raising the peak.", "a": "Principle: the memory bottleneck for big models is backward; reach effective batch via grad-accum, not by stacking per-device. This one is essentially fully general."}
{"id": "D10", "principle": "models-take-shortcuts-ablate-to-detect", "level": "L3", "context": "Under TF the audio head top-1 is 62%; you blank the text row and accuracy goes UP to 63%.", "q": "What does this mean?", "naive": "Accuracy is high, it learned well.", "why": "The audio head scores high just by continuing its own acoustic history (inertia), and text is unused; blanking text only removes noise, so it goes up not down.", "a": "Principle: a model will take the easiest predictive shortcut and ignore harder conditions; detect it with ablation (drop the condition, see if it drops). audio-head-ignores-text is the instance."}
{"id": "D11", "principle": "small-additive-signal-gets-swamped", "level": "L3", "context": "The user/asst audio streams query the same speech_embeddings, distinguished only by a tiny additive role constant.", "q": "What happens?", "naive": "It should be able to separate them.", "why": "The role constant trains to only ~1e-5, while the code-embedding norm is ~0.6 — the additive bias is swamped, and the model can't tell user from asst -> stream crosstalk.", "a": "Principle: a small additive signal gets swamped by a large shared table; to distinguish you need comparable magnitude or separate parameterization. role-emb collapse is the instance."}
{"id": "D12", "principle": "a-gate-copied-across-regimes-misfires", "level": "L3", "context": "In base, text/audio are mutually exclusive, so zeroing audio at text groups via is_speech is safe; you copy it to the dual-stream layout.", "q": "What's the side effect?", "naive": "Nothing, text groups have no audio anyway.", "why": "In dual-stream every group has text+audio co-existing; the copied is_speech zeros BOTH the user condition AND the asst's own audio feedback -> it loses its own context mid-utterance.", "a": "Principle: a gate copied from one regime (mutual exclusion) misfires in another (co-existence); check that its premise still holds. is_speech is the instance."}
{"id": "D13", "principle": "dedup-on-the-full-identity-key", "level": "L2", "context": "You split train/val and dedup by session_id, so a session isn't in both at once.", "q": "Is dedup by session_id enough?", "naive": "Sure, splitting by session is fine.", "why": "A session is cut into many time windows; deduping by session_id alone can put some windows in train and others in val -> leakage -> inflated eval.", "a": "Principle: dedup train/val on the FULL identity key, not a partial one. (session, window) is the instance."}
{"id": "D14", "principle": "config-from-many-sources-silently-overrides", "level": "L2", "when": "sbatch|torchrun|scheduler|deepspeed", "context": "sbatch says --lr_scheduler_type cosine, and you also use DeepSpeed, whose ds_config has a scheduler block.", "q": "Is it definitely cosine?", "naive": "It says so, so yes.", "why": "When DeepSpeed owns scheduling, its config's scheduler block takes priority and silently overrides the HF flag; you think cosine, it's actually linear.", "a": "Principle: config from multiple sources silently overrides — always print the EFFECTIVE value. DeepSpeed-over-sbatch is the instance."}
{"id": "D15", "principle": "hparams-dont-transfer-across-regimes", "level": "L2", "when": "sbatch|torchrun|\\blr\\b|learning_rate", "context": "base was trained with LoRA at 2e-5, and you want to full-FT the whole backbone, reusing 2e-5.", "q": "Is 2e-5 right too?", "naive": "Just copy base's.", "why": "LoRA updates few parameters, so 2e-5 fits; full-FT updates all parameters, and the same LR steps too big -> overfit.", "a": "Principle: hyperparameters don't transfer across training regimes (LoRA<->full-FT); re-scale per regime. 2e-5 is the instance."}
{"id": "E1", "principle": "beware-the-trivially-predictable-majority", "level": "L3", "when": "ablation|accuracy|准确率|\\bmetric\\b|指标", "context": "Under TF the audio head per-frame top-1 is 62%. But ~70% of the frames in the window are silence, and only a small part is real speech.", "q": "62% is high — does it mean it learned well?", "naive": "62% isn't low, learned well.", "why": "Silence codes repeat, so copying the previous frame is ~100% right; 62% is almost entirely 'got the silence right' — a trivial score. The real speech region is only 12%.", "a": "Principle: when the majority class is trivially predictable, an aggregate metric is hijacked by it; split by class/region. silence-dominated accuracy is the instance."}
{"id": "E2", "principle": "free-running-not-teacher-forced-is-the-test", "level": "L3", "when": "teacher.?forc|准确率|free.?run|自由生成", "context": "You measured per-cb accuracy under teacher-forcing (feed GT past each step), and it's high.", "q": "TF accuracy is high — is the model good?", "naive": "TF accuracy is high, so yes.", "why": "Given a perfect past, continuing the next frame is easy; free-running feeds the model its own predictions, one error compounds, and a pure-inertia model never recovers. TF measures local, generation measures global.", "a": "Principle: teacher-forced overstates; free-running generation is the real test, and the gap between them is itself the diagnostic. audio-head TF-high/generation-collapses is the instance."}
{"id": "E3", "principle": "eval-conditions-must-equal-deployment", "level": "L3", "when": "onset.?floor|forced.?text|crutch|强制", "context": "You used onset_floor to force the model to start speaking after the GT user-end, and turn-taking looks great.", "q": "Can you conclude turn-taking is good?", "naive": "It works, so yes.", "why": "onset_floor secretly hands the model the answer to 'when to start' (the hardest sub-task) from GT; you're measuring the easier 'answer the question'. Deployment has no GT user-end -> autonomous onset is exposed -> it breaks.", "a": "Principle: the eval's information set + task difficulty must EQUAL deployment; giving it help deployment won't have = inflation. the onset_floor crutch is the instance."}
{"id": "R1", "principle": "resolve-the-load-bearing-unknown-first", "level": "L3", "context": "Your plan has ~20 decisions; several are still open, and you're about to start working through them.", "q": "Which open decision do you tackle first?", "naive": "Top-to-bottom, or the easy ones first.", "why": "Open questions aren't equal: usually ONE is load-bearing — if it flips, the whole plan changes — and it's often the cheapest to test (e.g. 'is the base checkpoint's audio head even trained?'). Working the others first risks building on a foundation that may not exist.", "a": "Principle: find the load-bearing unknown — the one open question that most gates the rest / the cheapest test that could invalidate the whole plan — and resolve it FIRST. Critical-path before convenience. The 'is stage4 trained?' blocker is the instance."}
{"id": "R2", "principle": "drive-dont-menu", "level": "L2", "context": "You just finished a plan with many decisions and want to keep momentum.", "q": "How do you hand it back — a list of all decisions with 'which to change?', or something else?", "naive": "List everything and let the user pick what to do next.", "why": "A menu of N options offloads the prioritization back to the human and kills momentum; it reads as 'I don't know what matters'. Energy and focus come from one committed next action in pursuit, not a buffet.", "a": "Principle: drive, don't menu — name the single next action on the main thread and pursue it; never end on a flat 'which of these do you want?' that dumps the priority decision back on the user."}
{"id": "R3", "principle": "motivation-needs-a-compass", "level": "L3", "context": "Mid-project, work keeps drifting into busywork (running tools, polishing side things) and losing steam.", "q": "What three things must stay visible to keep work focused and motivated?", "naive": "Just the task list / the next ticket.", "why": "Focus needs a compass with three layers: the GOAL (why we're here — long-term drive), the MAIN THREAD (the one blocker that gates progress now — focus), and the NEXT ACTION (what to do this moment — momentum). Lose any one and you drift: no goal = aimless, no main thread = scattered, no next action = stalled.", "a": "Principle: keep the compass — goal · main thread · next action — always lit; drifting into busywork is the symptom of one of the three going dark."}
{"id": "D16", "principle": "look-at-the-data-before-trusting-it", "level": "L2", "when": "data|样本|sample|分布|profile", "context": "A new data source: the aggregate stats look normal and training loss drops smoothly.", "q": "Is that enough to trust the data?", "naive": "The averages look fine and loss is dropping, so the data's good.", "why": "Aggregates and a falling loss are blind to per-sample garbage — 30% music inside 'speech', a wrong-language slice, mislabeled turns; a data bug is silent, the loss drops happily while the model learns garbage. Only a human opening and looking/listening to real samples at each stage catches a bug that lives in the bytes.", "a": "Principle: trust a source only after a human has looked/listened to N random samples at every stage; aggregates and loss-drop are not evidence the data is right. The 'fine in the mean' source is the instance."}
{"id": "D17", "principle": "measure-dont-assume-the-distribution", "level": "L2", "when": "data|distribution|分布|histogram|hours|language|sample.?rate", "context": "Someone tells you a source is '16kHz Chinese conversational speech'.", "q": "How do you treat that description?", "naive": "It's the spec, take it as fact and move on.", "why": "Every claim about data is a hypothesis; the killer hides in the tail and the mode — a 10% English or music slice, a sample-rate outlier — that a one-line description and a mean never show.", "a": "Principle: measure the distribution on a real sample (histogram sr/language/duration/speakers) rather than believe the description; the bug is in the tail/mode. 'it's 16kHz zh' is the instance."}
{"id": "D18", "principle": "data-must-contain-the-behavior-you-want", "level": "L3", "when": "turn|dialogue|对话|behavior|行为|duplex", "context": "You fine-tune on single-speaker TTS turns to teach the model when to wait for the user to finish, but it never waits.", "q": "Most likely root cause?", "naive": "Boundary loss weight too low, or it needs more steps.", "why": "Single-speaker TTS has no real human-stops-then-other-starts events; the behavior 'wait for the turn-end' is simply absent from the data, so no loss weight or extra steps can conjure it. A model only learns what the data contains.", "a": "Principle: a behavior must be PRESENT in the data to be learnable; if it's absent, fix the data, not the loss/steps. Turn-taking from single-speaker TTS is the instance."}
{"id": "D19", "principle": "provenance-trust-ladder", "level": "L2", "when": "timestamp|provenance|owner|说.{0,4}有|据说", "context": "Your data-contract says the source has per-sentence timestamps — because the data owner told you so.", "q": "How much do you trust that fact?", "naive": "The owner made the data, so it's reliable.", "why": "A fact's trust depends on HOW you know it: measured-from-a-sample > read-from-code/config > human-asserted. A human assertion is the weakest and is often contradicted by the bytes — e.g. the packed shards turn out to have no timestamps at all.", "a": "Principle: tag every data fact with its provenance (measured > read > asserted) and mark human-asserted facts VERIFY until measured. 'the owner said there are timestamps' is the instance."}
{"id": "D20", "principle": "measure-the-data-contract-before-you-train", "level": "L3", "when": "data_contract|unmeasured|contract|sbatch|launch", "context": "Months in, the model is bad and you suspect the architecture; the data-contract still has UNKNOWN fields.", "q": "What does the data-contract discipline say to rule out first?", "naive": "Data was fine at kickoff; retune the model/loss.", "why": "An UNKNOWN contract means nobody measured the data — you've been flying blind. A 'green' contract would only mean 'the checks I thought of passed', never 'the data is fine'; the bad result may be unmeasured data, not the model.", "a": "Principle: before blaming the model, the data-contract must be MEASURED (or each gap explicitly owned); 'green' = measured-or-acknowledged, never assumed. The UNKNOWN-contract regression is the instance."}
# --- canonical rows for principles surfaced by the `proposals` + `kimi` meta-projects ---
# (reconciled onto the single bank; project-local aliases live in research/principle_adapter.json)
{"id": "A1", "principle": "append-only-record", "level": "L2", "context": "A bet recorded in an append-only collection failed; you're tempted to delete it and reuse the slot.", "q": "A recorded item failed — what happens to it?", "naive": "Delete it / roll it back so the collection only holds live items.", "why": "The value of a history record is remembering what was tried and WHY it failed; a mutable store that overwrites on each change loses every prior state. (hansard proposals: plan.py:49 overwrites plan.<name>.jsonl every run.)", "a": "Principle: the record is append-only — a failed item stays with a terminal status and an outcome note; deleting or rolling back silently destroys the institutional memory the record exists to keep."}
{"id": "A2", "principle": "flat-independent-collection", "level": "L2", "context": "You're modeling how many peer items coexist in one store.", "q": "Is there one privileged 'active' item the others defer to?", "naive": "Yes — one active at a time, the rest inactive.", "why": "A single-active model (e.g. .active-project read once and overwritten) silently discards every other item and couples things that should be independent. (hansard: plan.py:34-46, new_project.py:67.)", "a": "Principle: model peers as a flat, independent collection with no privileged 'active' singleton — N items coexist with no forced relationship."}
{"id": "A3", "principle": "status-at-the-right-altitude", "level": "L2", "context": "Items already carry a status (e.g. open|decided|verified); now the aggregate that holds them needs one too.", "q": "Reuse the item-level status field for the aggregate's lifecycle?", "naive": "Yes — the aggregate is 'done' when its items are.", "why": "An aggregate can be 'abandoned' while every component was 'decided' — a different axis. One field for both makes the aggregate's real state unrepresentable. (hansard: per-decision status at plan.py:31 vs a proposal's lifecycle.)", "a": "Principle: put each status at its right altitude — the aggregate's lifecycle (draft/accepted/superseded/abandoned) is a distinct axis from its components' status."}
{"id": "A4", "principle": "lineage-pointer", "level": "L2", "context": "An append-only history piles up many versions of the same thing.", "q": "How do you make that history navigable across versions?", "naive": "Sort by timestamp — order alone shows the lineage.", "why": "Timestamp order can't express branch/supersede relationships; the history is navigable only if each entry records WHAT it supersedes (an explicit parent pointer).", "a": "Principle: append-only history needs an explicit lineage pointer — each entry records what it supersedes, or the version lineage is silently lost."}
{"id": "A5", "principle": "overview-first", "level": "L1", "context": "A report renders exactly one item's page, with no index across items.", "q": "What makes a many-item collection 'manageable' on a surface?", "naive": "Just render each item's own page — open the one you want.", "why": "With no index you can't see the collection at all. Manageable = an overview that lists every item with status + filter BEFORE drilling in (Shneiderman: overview, zoom, detail). (hansard: viz renders one project, no index.)", "a": "Principle: overview first — list+filter across ALL items before drilling into any single one."}
{"id": "A6", "principle": "diff-not-dump", "level": "L2", "context": "You need to compare two versions; the tool can only show full pages today.", "q": "How should the surface show the difference between two versions?", "naive": "Show both full versions side by side and let the reader spot differences.", "why": "Dumping both full versions makes the reader recompute the diff by eye; the useful thing is the delta — which parts were added, changed, dropped, restatused.", "a": "Principle: comparison is a diff, not a dump — surface the delta, not two full versions to eyeball."}
{"id": "A7", "principle": "enforcement-needs-a-target", "level": "L3", "context": "An online guard keyed off a single 'active' context; you're dropping that singleton.", "q": "With no single active context, what does the guard enforce against?", "naive": "It keeps working — just silently point it at the newest item.", "why": "The guard binds to a subject; remove the singleton without an explicit retarget and it has nothing to act on and goes quiet. (hansard: router/planaware/surfacer all key off .active-project via plan._active().)", "a": "Principle: enforcement needs an explicit target — drop the singleton a guard keyed off and you must give it a new subject, or it silently enforces nothing."}
{"id": "A8", "principle": "backward-compatible-migration", "level": "L2", "context": "Existing artifacts in the old schema must keep working after a model change.", "q": "How do today's artifacts enter the new model?", "naive": "Require each to be re-authored from scratch under the new schema.", "why": "Reads should degrade gracefully on absent fields; treating each existing artifact as the first instance of the new shape means nothing old has to be rewritten. (hansard: plan.py:54 already returns [] on absent file.)", "a": "Principle: migrate backward-compatibly — let existing artifacts keep working (treat each as the first instance of the new shape), don't force a rewrite of everything old."}
{"id": "A9", "principle": "host-channel-fit", "level": "L3", "context": "The host can only block — it can't inject context/system messages the way your home platform does.", "q": "How do you deliver soft signals (a nudge, an alert) on a block-only host?", "naive": "Emit the same context-injection payload your home platform reads.", "why": "A channel the host never reads sends the signal nowhere. Fold what you can into a channel it DOES have (e.g. escalate -> a block whose reason carries the alert) and explicitly drop what has no path. (hansard kimi: runner.py only parses permissionDecision==deny; stdout never injected.)", "a": "Principle: fit the channel to the host — fold a signal into a channel the host actually consumes, or drop it explicitly; never emit on a channel it never reads."}
{"id": "A10", "principle": "fail-open-never-exit-block", "level": "L3", "context": "A guard/hook wraps every action; a bug or missing script in it could lock the session.", "q": "How do you keep the guard's own bug from locking the system?", "naive": "Exit non-zero to block when something goes wrong — safer to stop.", "why": "A guard that can fail closed can lock the whole system on its own bug. Blocking must go through one explicit narrow channel; any error/timeout/missing-piece must ALLOW. (hansard kimi: runner.py:71 blocks only on exit 2; hansard never exits 2, wraps in try->allow.)", "a": "Principle: fail open — a guard must ALLOW on any internal error/timeout/missing piece and block only via one explicit narrow channel, so its own bug can never lock the system."}
{"id": "A11", "principle": "report-as-gate", "level": "L2", "context": "You want to gate a low-quality output and have it rewritten, not just rejected.", "q": "What does the host need to provide for an output-gate to force a rewrite?", "naive": "Nothing special — any hook that can reject is enough.", "why": "Rewrite needs the host to RE-INVOKE the turn with the rejection reason fed back as the next input (guarded against re-entry). Without that re-feed a gate can only reject. (hansard: reportcheck Stop block; kimi kimisoul.py:656-670 _turn(reason) once.)", "a": "Principle: a report-gate works wherever the host re-invokes the turn with the rejection reason as the next input — block once, reason becomes the rewrite prompt."}
{"id": "A12", "principle": "keys-must-be-canonical-complete-and-unique", "level": "L2", "context": "You store and look up many items by a key — a name, a tool id, a record id.", "q": "The key is 'roughly unique' but not in one canonical form. What can go wrong?", "naive": "Roughly unique is fine — exact spelling/format doesn't matter.", "why": "A mis-formatted key silently misses on exact-match; an under-specified key collides so a later write overwrites an earlier one; a non-unique key collapses distinct items onto one — all with no exception. (hansard: proposals addressing N coexisting bets; kimi normalizing Shell->Bash before the matcher.)", "a": "Principle: a lookup/storage key must be in ONE canonical form, include every distinguishing dimension, and be unique per item — or it silently drops, collides, or collapses."}
{"id": "A13", "principle": "side-effect-hook-must-fire-on-every-branch", "level": "L2", "context": "A side-effect hook records state a later consumer depends on; it's wired on the common path.", "q": "It fires on the common path — is that enough?", "naive": "Yes — the common path is what runs almost always.", "why": "Alternate branches (forcing/prefix/replacement; PreCompact vs SessionEnd) still produce the state but never emit it, leaving the consumer missing data with no exception. (hansard kimi: harvest must fire on PreCompact AND SessionEnd.)", "a": "Principle: every branch that produces consumer-needed state must call the side-effect hook; wiring only the common branch silently drops the data on all the others."}
# --- canonical rows filling bank gaps surfaced by the example project ---
{"id": "A14", "principle": "fresh-not-continued-when-the-design-changed", "level": "L2", "when": "resume|continue|从.{0,6}继续|checkpoint|ckpt|bootstrap|init.{0,4}from", "context": "You are starting a new run after changing the design/loss/data, and a previous experimental checkpoint is sitting right there to resume from.", "q": "Bootstrap the new run from that prior experimental checkpoint, or from a clean base?", "naive": "Resume the prior checkpoint — it is further along, why waste the progress.", "why": "A prior experimental ckpt carries forward its rot (the old design/loss/data baked into its weights); after a design change those must be re-learned, and continuing hides the change under stale state. (hansard example: each duplex run starts fresh from base, never from a previous duplex ckpt.)", "a": "Principle: when the design/loss/data changed, start fresh from a clean base; continuing a prior experimental checkpoint carries its rot forward."}
{"id": "A15", "principle": "rule-out-the-trunk-before-blaming-a-branch", "level": "L2", "when": "epoch|under.?train|训练.{0,4}够|loss.?weight|blame|root.?cause|为什么.{0,4}差", "context": "A run produces a bad result and you immediately suspect a specific design choice (a loss weight, a branch of the architecture).", "q": "Before blaming that design choice, what do you rule out first?", "naive": "It is clearly the design choice — start tuning that loss weight.", "why": "The symptom often is not where you are looking: under-training or a preprocessing bug (the trunk) mimics a design fault (a branch). (hansard example: robotic audio looked like a loss-weights bug; the real cause was 1.26 epochs + a power-preprocessing bug — a trunk fault.)", "a": "Principle: rule out a trunk fault (under-training, a preprocessing bug) before blaming a specific design branch; the symptom often is not where you are looking."}
